<TEXT>
 Surrealist painter <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>, suffering from pneumonia and possible heart failure, was hospitalized on Sunday, news reports said. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponsati </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>'s personal physician, said <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>, 84, was in stable condition at the Hospital Comarcal in <LOCATION> Figueras </LOCATION>, according to the official <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> news agency <ORGANIZATION> EFE </ORGANIZATION>. A spokesman at the hospital declined comment but said the hospital would make a statement Monday morning, the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> news agency Agence France-Presse reported. <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>, who was born in this small Catalonian town in northeastern <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> border, is known for his scenes of limp watches draped over troubled landscapes and hundreds of other works of surrealism. Since the death of his wife in 1982, <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>'s physical condition has deteriorated to the point where he requires constant medical supervision. A fire at his home in nearby <LOCATION> Gerona </LOCATION> in 1984 gave him serious respiratory problems, and he has been on a respirator the past two years.
