 In the past month, Soviet statements from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> have warned that stepped up attacks by U.S.-backed guerrillas threaten to derail a withdrawal of Soviet troops. In an agreement signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> last April, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> promised to withdraw an estimated 100,000 troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> from May 15 to Feb. 15. Half left by Aug. 15 and despite strongly worded warnings by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, it promised to meet the February deadline.
