<HEAD>Nearly 440 Die in Weekend Traffic Accidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 440 Americans died on the nation's highways over the long holiday weekend as millions took to the roads to visit family and friends in celebration of Thanksgiving. The number of highway fatalities this year was 438, down from last year's total of 494 during the four-day Thanksgiving period, which for counting purposes extended from 6 p.m. local time Wednesday to midnight local time Sunday. The highest toll for the holiday was recorded in 1968, when 764 people were killed. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said about 390 people could be expected to be killed on the highways during a four-day, non-holiday weekend at this time of year. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, with 59 highway deaths, reported more fatalities than any other state. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> was second with 35. Four states _ <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> _ reported no deaths.
